<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-03-02-02-0175-0003-fn-0010-ptr" id="GEWN-03-02-02-0175-0003-fn-0010">10</a>

   <p>This amendment corrects an error apparently made in taking many of the Continental articles of war from the Massachusetts articles. Continental article 2, which regulates behavior at religious services, is the first Massachusetts article, and Continental article 3, which prohibits profanity, is the second of the Massachusetts articles. Continental article 1, which does not appear in the Massachusetts articles, concerns the subscribing of the articles of war and includes no punishments (<span class="ref-st" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ Worthington Chauncey Ford et al., eds. &lt;i&gt;Journals of the Continental Congress, 1774-1789&lt;/i&gt;. 34 vols. Washington, D.C., 190437. ]"><span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">JCC</span>,</span> 2:112; <span class="ref-st" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ William Lincoln, ed. &lt;i&gt;The Journals of Each Provincial Congress of Massachusetts in 1774 and 1775, and of the Committee of Safety&lt;/i&gt;. Boston, 1838. (Microfilm Collection of Early State Records). ]"><span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">Mass. Prov. Congress Journals</span></span>, 12122).</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-03-02-02-0175-0003-fn-0011-ptr" id="GEWN-03-02-02-0175-0003-fn-0011">11</a>

   <p>Article 5 concerns mutiny and sedition (<span class="ref-st" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ Worthington Chauncey Ford et al., eds. &lt;i&gt;Journals of the Continental Congress, 1774-1789&lt;/i&gt;. 34 vols. Washington, D.C., 190437. ]"><span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">JCC</span>,</span> 113).</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-03-02-02-0175-0003-fn-0012-ptr" id="GEWN-03-02-02-0175-0003-fn-0012">12</a>

   <p>Article 20 punishes drunkenness on guard or other duty, while article 21 deals with sentries discovered sleeping at their posts (ibid., 115).</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-03-02-02-0175-0003-fn-0013-ptr" id="GEWN-03-02-02-0175-0003-fn-0013">13</a>

   <p>Article 17 provides that no officer or soldier shall lie out of his quarters or camp, without leave from the commanding officer of the regiment (ibid.).</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-03-02-02-0175-0003-fn-0014-ptr" id="GEWN-03-02-02-0175-0003-fn-0014">14</a>

   <p>Before amendment, article 25 read: Whatsoever officer or soldier shall shamefully abandon any post committed to his charge, or shall speak words inducing others to do the like, in time of an engagement, shall suffer death immediately (ibid., 116).</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-03-02-02-0175-0003-fn-0015-ptr" id="GEWN-03-02-02-0175-0003-fn-0015">15</a>

   <p>Article 29, which secures all public stores taken in the enemys camp or magazines . . . for the use of the United Colonies, previously provided no punishment. Article 15 punishes any officer convicted of selling or wasting Continental stores by reduction to a private centinel. Guilty private soldiers were to suffer such punishment as shall be ordered by a regimental court-martial (ibid., 11416).</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-03-02-02-0175-0003-fn-0016-ptr" id="GEWN-03-02-02-0175-0003-fn-0016">16</a>

   <p>The offense in article 30 is leaving ones post or colours, in time of an engagement, to go in search of plunder (ibid., 116).</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-03-02-02-0175-0003-fn-0017-ptr" id="GEWN-03-02-02-0175-0003-fn-0017">17</a>

   <p>Article 55 provides that every officer commanding a regiment, troop, or company, shall, upon notice given to him by the Commissary of the musters, or from one of his deputies, assemble the regiment, troop, or company under his command, in the next convenient place for their being mustered (ibid., 120).</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-03-02-02-0175-0003-fn-0018-ptr" id="GEWN-03-02-02-0175-0003-fn-0018">18</a>

   <p>Article 57 requires the commanding officer of each regiment, troop, or company at a muster to present certificates signed by himself, signifying how long such officers, non-commissioned officers, and soldiers, who shall not appear at the said muster, have been absent, and the reason of their absence (ibid.).</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-03-02-02-0175-0003-fn-0019-ptr" id="GEWN-03-02-02-0175-0003-fn-0019">19</a>

   <p>Item 7 in Congresss instructions to the committee of conference requires the committee to include in its inquiry not only the Forces necessary to be kept in the Massachusetts Bay but in the Northern Department (ibid., 3:271).</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-03-02-02-0175-0003-fn-0020-ptr" id="GEWN-03-02-02-0175-0003-fn-0020">20</a>

   <p>This query comes from <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-03-02-02-0175-0002" class="document">GWs Questions for the Committee</a><span class="choice deletion" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover_choice ] header=[]  body=[ Deleted: ' printed above' &lt;span style='font-size: 90%'&gt;[[2014-12-02]]&lt;/span&gt; ]"><img alt="deletion" src="images/deletion_mark-trans.png" style="border:none;vertical-align: text-bottom; padding-right:2px"/></span>.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-03-02-02-0175-0003-fn-0021-ptr" id="GEWN-03-02-02-0175-0003-fn-0021">21</a>

   <p>This query is also included in <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-03-02-02-0175-0002" class="document">Questions for the Committee</a>.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-03-02-02-0175-0003-fn-0022-ptr" id="GEWN-03-02-02-0175-0003-fn-0022">22</a>
	
   <p>See <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-03-01-02-0292" class="document">Instructions to Nicholson Broughton, 2 Sept.</a>, and <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-03-02-02-0168" class="document">Instructions to Captains Nicholson Broughton and John Selman, 16 Oct. 1775</a>.</p>

</div>
<span class="pb center" title="page number in print edition (no page scan available)" id="GEWN-03-02-02-pb-0205">[205]</span>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-03-02-02-0175-0003-fn-0023-ptr" id="GEWN-03-02-02-0175-0003-fn-0023">23</a>

   <p>See <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-03-02-02-0115" class="document">Council of War, 8 Oct. 1775</a>.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-03-02-02-0175-0003-fn-0024-ptr" id="GEWN-03-02-02-0175-0003-fn-0024">24</a>

   <p>See ibid.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-03-02-02-0175-0003-fn-0025-ptr" id="GEWN-03-02-02-0175-0003-fn-0025">25</a>

   <p>See <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-03-02-02-0024" class="document">General Orders, 21 Sept. 1775</a>, and <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-03-02-02-0025" class="document">GW to Hancock, that date</a>.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-03-02-02-0175-0003-fn-0026-ptr" id="GEWN-03-02-02-0175-0003-fn-0026">26</a>

   <p>In the PCC copy Congress changed the last part of this answer to: Citizens for Citizens officers for officer[s] of equal Rank &amp; Soldier for Soldier.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-03-02-02-0175-0003-fn-0027-ptr" id="GEWN-03-02-02-0175-0003-fn-0027">27</a>

   <p>In the PCC copy Congress inserted here the words if they do not Chuse to Enlist into other Corps.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-03-02-02-0175-0003-fn-0028-ptr" id="GEWN-03-02-02-0175-0003-fn-0028">28</a>

   <p>See <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-03-02-02-0174" class="document">Council of War, 18 Oct. 1775</a>.</p>

</div>
